{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"95704772-7fc9-432a-961d-4b0f8483df3f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:~/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` during collection for browser-based analysis).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) container image instead.\n- For production, prefer `dotnet-monitor` — it exposes an HTTP API for on-demand trace collection without exec'ing in.\n- Add `--buffersize 256` if you're seeing dropped events under heavy load.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"379fcf2f-8719-422f-aecc-d4889e89a42a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I should provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":418,"requestId":"2162:38F59:3F38A2:49611F:69F00D60"},"id":"68091dd8-0ba5-4c73-849e-bf94ce41b8c5","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:29:15.819Z","parentId":"685be231-912c-4316-9a0f-ee3f15d2d7e6"}
